As isothermal $\Delta \mathrm{U}=0$
and process is irreversible
$\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{Q}=-\mathrm{W}=-\left[-\mathrm{P}_{\text {ext }}\left(\mathrm{V}_2-\mathrm{V}_1\right)\right] \\
& \mathrm{Q}=5(20-60)=-200 \mathrm{~atm}-\mathrm{L}
\end{aligned}$

For isothermal process $(\Delta T=0)$
$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta S & =R \ell \mathrm{n} \frac{P_1}{P_2}=8.314 \ell \mathrm{n} 2 \\
& =8.314 \times 0.693=5.76 \mathrm{JK}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

Energy required for $1 \mathrm{Cl}_2$ molecule $=\frac{242 \times 10^3}{\mathrm{~N}_{\mathrm{A}}}$ Joules.
This energy is contained in photon of wavelength ' $\lambda$ '.
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\mathrm{hc}}{\lambda}=\mathrm{E} \Rightarrow \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \times 3 \times 10^8}{\lambda}=\frac{242 \times 10^3}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} \\
& \lambda=4947 Å \approx 494 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{aligned}
$$

$\Delta G=\Delta G^{\circ}+R T \ln Q$

At equilibrium; $\Delta G=0$ and $Q=K_{\mathrm{eq}}$

$$

\begin{array}{l}

\Rightarrow \Delta G^{\circ}=-2.303 \mathrm{RT} \log \mathrm{K}_{\mathrm{w}} \\

=-2.303 \times 8.314 \times 298 \times \log 10^{-14}

\end{array}

$$

$=79.9 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol} \approx 80 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$

Applying Hess's Law
$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta_{\mathrm{f}} \mathrm{H}^{\circ}= & \Delta_{\text {sub }} \mathrm{H}+\frac{1}{2} \Delta_{\text {diss }} \mathrm{H}+\text { I.E. }+\text { E.A }+\Delta_{\text {lattice }} \mathrm{H} \\
& -617=161+520+77+\text { E.A. }+(-1047) \\
& \text { E.A. }=-617+289=-328 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1} \\
& \therefore \text { electron affinity of fluorine } \\
& =-328 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$
